This question will resolve as Yes if, by December 31, 2030, there is a significant and publicly acknowledged instance where Formula 1 (F1) has influenced international relations or diplomacy. Significant influence includes, but is not limited to:
- An F1 event directly leading to a formal meeting or agreement between two or more countries;
- F1 being used as a platform for diplomatic engagement or to promote peace between nations;
- A country's decision to host or not host an F1 event leading to substantial changes in its international relationships or diplomatic stance.

The influence must be confirmed by official government statements or documentation from the countries involved. In the absence of such statements, credible reports from at least three major news organizations (BBC, The Guardian, Reuters, Bloomberg, New York Times, Washington Post) will be considered sufficient. Temporary or indirect influences, such as tourism boosts or increased international visibility, do not count towards this question's resolution.

Criterion for condition: This question will resolve as Yes if both of the following occur: (1) By December 31, 2025, the National Football League (NFL) has officially hosted a regular season or playoff game in a country that, at the time of the game, is under international sanctions by the United Nations, the European Union, the United States, or any other major international body. The game must be part of the official NFL season schedule, and not a pre-season or exhibition game. Confirmation must come from an official NFL announcement or credible news reports from at least three major news organizations (e.g., ESPN, BBC, The New York Times, The Washington Post). In the event that sanctions are lifted on a country after the announcement of the game but before the game itself, the question will still resolve as Yes if the sanctions were in place at the time of the announcement. Temporary or partial sanctions specifically targeting individuals or entities within the country do not qualify; the sanctions must be country-wide. (2) By December 31, 2029, a peer-reviewed study is published demonstrating a significant impact of climate change on soccer playing conditions worldwide. Significant impact is defined as changes that affect the health and performance of players, the scheduling and locations of matches, or the physical conditions of playing fields. The study must be recognized by a leading scientific organization or journal in the field of climate science, sports science, or a related field. In the absence of a single comprehensive study, a consensus among multiple studies published in reputable scientific journals may also satisfy this criterion. The resolution will rely on reports from authoritative sources such as the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), World Health Organization (WHO), or major sports governing bodies like FIFA. In the event of conflicting reports, the majority consensus among these sources will determine the outcome. Edge cases, such as localized impacts not reflective of global trends, do not count towards this question's resolution.

